title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p><fr:strong>Existence:</fr:strong> We see that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\ker (\varphi )]]></fr:tex> is closed under multiplication since for any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x,y\in \ker (\varphi )]]></fr:tex> has <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi (xy)=\varphi (x)\varphi (y)=ee=e]]></fr:tex> which means <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[xy\in \ker (\varphi )]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>We also see that for any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in \ker (\varphi )]]></fr:tex> that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi (x)=e=e^{-1}=\varphi (x)^{-1}=\varphi (x^{-1})]]></fr:tex> which means <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x^{-1}\in \ker (\varphi )]]></fr:tex>. So <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\ker (\varphi )]]></fr:tex> is closed under inverting elements.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Hence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\ker (\varphi )]]></fr:tex> is a group and its underlying set is a subset of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
